crusades00thom|url-access=registration|location=Ann Arbor|publisher= University of Michigan|year=2005}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"rCeS6\">{{cite web |url=http://www.channel4.com/history/microsites/H/history/a-b/blackdeath.html |title=The Black Death |accessdate=2008-08-13 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080625094232/http://www.channel4.com/history/microsites/H/history/a-b/blackdeath.html |archivedate=25 June 2008 |df=dmy-all}}, Channel 4 \u2013 History.</ref>\n<ref name=\"nbpyu\">Runciman Fall. p. 60</ref>\n<ref name=\"cJRwI\">Norwich Short Byz. Hist. p. 373</ref>\n<ref name=\"MBVR8\">name=\"norwichshortbyzhist\"/>{{rp|373}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"qGd6u\">{{Cite book| publisher = Hachette Books| isbn = 978-1-4013-0558-1| last = Crowley| first = Roger| title = 1453: The Holy War for Constantinople and the Clash of Islam and the West| year= 2013}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"f6GY9\">Michael Spilling, ed., Battles That Changed History: Key Battles That Decided the Fate of Nations ( London, Amber Books Ltd. 2010) p. 187.</ref>\n<ref name=\"sQMpP\">Leonardo di Chio, ''Letter'', 930C.</ref>\n<ref name=\"q6rsq\">{{cite book |last=Davis|first=Paul|title=100 Decisive Battles|year=1999|publisher=Oxford|isbn=978-0-19-514366-9|page=166}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"n61Q6\">Arnold (2001) p. 111</ref>\n<ref name=\"bZgqW\">{{cite web |url=http://www.economist.com/node/346800?story_id=346800 |work=The Economist |title=The fall of Constantinople |date=23 December 1999 |access-date=11 December 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604214149/http://www.economist.com/node/346800?story_id=346800 |archive-date=4 June 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"MoRBA\">Crowley (2005), pp. 150\u2013154</ref>\n<ref name=\"FdrIR\">Marios Philippides and Walter K. Hanak, ''The Siege and the Fall of Constantinople in 1453'', (Ashgate Publishing, 2011), 520.</ref>\n<ref name=\"JRaLV\">From Jean Chartier, ''Chronicle of Charles VII, king of France'', MS Bnf Fran\u00e7ais 2691, 