33.1</center> || style=\"background: #{{Storm colour|storm}};\" | <center>Tropical Storm</center>\n|-\n| [[Typhoon Parma (2009)|Parma]] || ''Pepeng'' || <center>October 1\u201311</center> || <center>465</center> || <center>570.7</center> || style=\"background: #{{Storm colour|typhoon}};\" | <center>Typhoon</center>\n|-\n| [[2009 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Melor (Quedan)|Melor]] || ''Quedan'' || <center>----</center> || <center>----</center> || <center>----</center> || <center>----</center>\n|-\n| [[Typhoon Lupit (2009)|Lupit]] || ''Ramil'' || <center>October 22\u201323</center> || <center>0</center> || <center>Minimal</center> || style=\"background: #{{Storm colour|typhoon}};\" | <center>Typhoon</center>\n|-\n| [[2009 Pacific typhoon season#Typhoon Mirinae (Santi)|Mirinae]] || ''Santi'' || <center>October 30\u201331</center> || <center>29</center> || <center>10.4</center> || style=\"background: #{{Storm colour|typhoon}};\" | <center>Typhoon</center>\n|-\n| [[2009 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Depression 24W (Tino)|24W]] || ''Tino'' || <center>----</center> || <center>----</center> || <center>----</center> || <center>----</center>\n|-\n| [[Typhoon urduja|27W]] || ''Urduja'' || <center>\tNovember 23\u201325</center> || <center>----</center> || <center>----</center> || style=\"background: #{{Storm colour|depression}};\" | <center>Tropical Depression</center>\n|-\n| [[Typhoon Nida (2009)|Nida]] || ''Vinta''  || <center>----</center> || <center>----</center> || <center>----</center> || <center>----</center>\n|-\n| <center>----</center> || <center>20</center> || <center>January 5 \u2013 <br>December 3</center> || <center>'''1124'''</center> || <center>'''903.139'''</center> || <center>----</center>\n|}\n{{clear}}\n\n==Seasonal activity==\n\n===January\u2013April===\nTropical Depression Auring, the first system to form in the western Pacific during 2009, produced heavy rainfall and flooding on [[Mindanao]] in early January, forcing 38,764&nbsp;people to evacuate to shelters from their homes. The flooding destroyed 294&nbsp;houses, killed two people, and left nine others missing.<ref>{{cite web|author=Rene Acosta |date=January 5, 2009 |title=Thousands of 'Auring' victims still in evacuation centers |publisher=Business Mirror |accessdate=January 5, 2009 |url=http://businessmirror.com.ph/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4147:thousands-of-auring-victims-still-in-evacuation-centers&catid=26:nation&Itemid=63 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100212224810/http://businessmirror.com.ph/index.php?option=com_content |archivedate=February 12, 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Rene F. Alima|work=Cebu Daily News|date=January 6, 2009|accessdate=May 10, 2009|title=Mother electrocuted in Talisay|url=http://globalnation.inquirer.net/cebudailynews/metro/view/20090106-181728/Mother-electrocuted-in-Talisay|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090802034117/http://globalnation.inquirer.net/cebudailynews/metro/view/20090106-181728/Mother-electrocuted-in-Talisay|archivedate=August 2, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"TSS1\">{{cite web|author=Cong B. Corrales|publisher=The Sun Star|date=January 7, 2009|accessdate=May 10, 2009|title=16 villages declared 'calamity areas'|url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/static/cag/2009/01/07/news/16.villages.declared.calamity.areas..html|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5l8cqm1VS?url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/static/cag/2009/01/07/news/16.villages.declared.calamity.areas..html|archivedate=November 8, 2009}}</ref> About 12,211 people were left stranded at ports due to dangerous conditions caused by the depression. An additional 14 trucks, 44 light cars, 75 passenger buses, 27 vessels and 295 rolling cargoes were also stranded.<ref>{{cite news|author=Helen Flores|date=January 5, 2009|title='Auring' threatens eastern Visayas |newspaper=The Philippine Star|accessdate=January 5, 2009|url=http://www.philstar.com/Article.aspx?ArticleId=429210&publicationSubCategoryId=63}}</ref> A total of 305 homes were destroyed and another 610 were damaged. In addition, an estimated 53&nbsp;hectares (130.9&nbsp;acres) of rice and 3.5&nbsp;hectares (8.6&nbsp;acres) of corn were damaged. About 43,851 people were affected by the depression and<ref name=\"NDCC1\">{{cite web|publisher=National Disaster Coordinating Council|title=Consolidated Report on Flash Floods in Cagayan de Oro City and Gingong City|accessdate=January 9, 2008|url=http://210.185.184.53/ndccWeb/images/ndccWeb/ndcc_advisory/effects_flshflood_in_cagayan_de_oro_2009/ndcc%20update%20consolidated%20report%206%20dec%2009.pdf|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5l8cyi9AT?url=http://210.185.184.53/ndccWeb/images/ndccWeb/ndcc_advisory/effects_flshflood_in_cagayan_de_oro_2009/ndcc%20update%20consolidated%20report%206%20dec%2009.pdf|archivedate=November 8, 2009}}</ref> damages from the depression were estimated at [[Philippine peso|PHP]]&nbsp;23&nbsp;million ($498,318&nbsp;US$).<ref name=\"RW1\">{{cite web|author=Government of the Philippines|publisher=Reliefweb|title=PGMA orders immediate rehabilitation of flood-ravaged areas in Regions X, XIII|date=January 9, 2008|accessdate=January 10, 2008|url=http://www.reliefweb.int/rw/rwb.nsf/db900SID/LSGZ-7N4J7D?OpenDocument&emid=TC-2009-000005-PHL}}</ref>\n\nLate on February 14, the remnants of Tropical Depression Bising brought scattered rainshowers across Southern [[Luzon]], [[Bicol Region]], and [[Visayas]], then dissipated. The rainfall led to mudslides on [[Cebu Island]] which blocked the Cebu Transcentral Highway.<ref>{{cite web|author=Staff Writer|publisher=Cebu News Online|date=February 14, 2009|accessdate=March 7, 2009|title=Cebu Transcentral Highway impassable due to landslide.|url=http://www.cebuonlinenews.com/20090214/992305-cebu-transcentral-highway-impassable-due-to-landslide/|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090220160711/http://www.cebuonlinenews.com/20090214/992305-cebu-transcentral-highway-impassable-due-to-landslide/|archivedate=February 20, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Staff Writer|newspaper=Manila Bulletin|date=February 15, 2009|accessdate=May 11, 2009|title=2 major roads impassable.|url=http://www.articlearchives.com/safety-accidents-disasters/disasters-landslides/2330777-1.html|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120505140029/http://www.articlearchives.com/safety-accidents-disasters/disasters-landslides/2330777-1.html|archivedate=May 5, 2012}}</ref> Heavy rains produced by the [[rainband|outer bands]] of Tropical Depression Crising caused flooding in western areas of the Philippines, affecting an estimated 2,500 people. The worst flooding occurred in [[Lucena, Philippines|Lucena City]] where ten villages were isolated. Areas along the [[Bucon River|Bucon]] and [[Inalmasinan River]]s were inundated and sustained significant crop losses. Several animals reportedly drowned in the region. Several roads were impassable due to landslides or were washed out by floodwaters. One bridge was destroyed in the town of Mercedes.<ref>{{cite web|author=Staff Writer|publisher=GMA News|date=May 2, 2009|accessdate=May 10, 2009|title='Crising' affects 500 families in Quezon, isolates Bicol towns|url=http://ph.news.yahoo.com/gma/20090501/tph-crising-affects-500-families-in-quez-ce44f36.html|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090505135139/http://ph.news.yahoo.com/gma/20090501/tph-crising-affects-500-families-in-quez-ce44f36.html|archivedate=May 5, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===May===\n[[File:STS Kujira 3 May 2009.jpg|thumb|left|Tropical Storm Kujira near the Philippines on May&nbsp;3]]\nWhile in the Philippine area of responsibility, Typhoon Kujira caused some 625,709,464 worth of damage to crops and livestock in Albay, Camarines Norte, Masbate and Sorsogon.  It also caused some 102 million pesos worth of damage to communal irrigation systems in the region.<ref name=\"damages\">{{cite web|url=http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/nation/regions/05/06/09/typhoon-dantes-death-toll-rise-27|title=Typhoon Dante's death toll rises to 27|date=May 12, 2009|publisher=[[ABS-CBN News and Current Affairs]]|accessdate=May 6, 2009}}</ref> The NDCC update as of 6&nbsp;am PST May 12 declared 28 dead, one missing and 5 injured. Further, 383,457 persons in 609 barangays of 60 municipalities and 4 cities in 5 provinces of Region V were affected by the storm. Damages are worth PhP 1,228,422,344&nbsp;million or PhP1.228&nbsp;billion of which PhP 625,709,464 are agricultural losses and PhP 529.525&nbsp;million in infrastructural. Houses destroyed were at 2387, of which 138 were total and 2249 partial.<ref name=\"NDCC sitrep 14\">{{cite web |url=http://210.185.184.53/ndccWeb/images/ndccWeb/ndcc_advisory/TD_DANTE/ndcc%20update%20sitrep14%20re%20effects%20of%20ts%20dante-06%20may%202009-6am.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=October 11, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110530005130/http://210.185.184.53/ndccWeb/images/ndccWeb/ndcc_advisory/TD_DANTE/ndcc%20update%20sitrep14%20re%20effects%20of%20ts%20dante-06%20may%202009-6am.pdf |archivedate=May 30, 2011  }}</ref>\n\n====Typhoon Chan-hom====\nA 48-hour rainfall was recorded throughout Luzon from May 6 to 8 peaking on May due to Typhoon Chan-hom. 7 Winds of 85\u2013140&nbsp;km/h combined with heavy rain damaged the provinces of [[Abra (province)|Abra]], [[Quirino]], [[Cagayan]], [[Apayao]], [[Ilocos Norte]], [[Aurora (province)|Aurora]] (further, these provinces received more than 200mm in 24 hours.) and [[Zambales]] (received more than 135&nbsp;mm in 24 hours). Rain was also heavy over [[Pampanga]] (receiving 145&nbsp;mm), [[Nueva Ecija]], [[Tarlac]], [[Bulacan]], [[Bataan]], [[Metro Manila]] and parts of southern Luzon. Moderate rain was also experienced over [[Quezon]] province and [[Bicol Region]]. (Cagayan and Isabela are not specified but are also flooded which can mean it may have experienced more than 50&nbsp;mm of rain. Moreover, [[Cagayan River]] flooded). As of May 10, about 65,000 people were left homeless in [[Ilocos Region]] and in [[Cordillera Administrative Region|Cordillera region]].\n\n[[File:Typhoon Chan-hom 2009-05-06.jpg|thumb|right|Typhoon Chan-hom near the Philippines on May&nbsp;6]]\nIn [[Bataan]], the flood was up to the waistline. Some residents were also evacuated. As of May&nbsp;8, at least 25 people were confirmed to have been killed by flooding and mudslides produced by Emong.<ref>{{cite news|author=Staff Writer |agency=Associated Press |date=May 8, 2009 |accessdate=May 8, 2009 |title=25 dead as typhoon hits Philippines: officials |url=http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5iTG4TkwtgvppwgMaHGi8R1rf8n7Q |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5gcPjbBVx?url=http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5iTG4TkwtgvppwgMaHGi8R1rf8n7Q |archivedate=May 8, 2009  }}</ref> Chan-hom further affected 4,000 people, caused 11 landslides, cost [[Philippine peso|PHP]]863,528 worth of crops in 55 hectares of land in [[Zambales]] and PHP4.4&nbsp;million worth of transmission lines in [[Pangasinan]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Staff Writer|publisher=GMA News|date=May 8, 2009|accessdate=May 8, 2009|title=Emong's death toll rises to 27; several missing|url=http://www.gmanews.tv/story/160507/Emongs-death-toll-rises-to-27-several-missing}}</ref>\n\nOn May 9, the number of fatalities increased to 26. Western Pangasinan was put under a [[state of calamity]], with the whole province registering at least 16 deaths. Deaths included those who drowned, buried under their collapsed homes and got hit by flying debris. In the town of [[Anda, Pangasinan|Anda]] in Pangasinan, \"90 percent\" of houses got their roofs blown away, with mango trees uprooted and cultured fishes washed away to the sea. In [[Ifugao (province)|Ifugao]], at least 10 deaths were blamed on landslides, while the bridges linking [[Lamut, Ifugao|Lamut]] and [[Bagabag, Nueva Vizcaya]] collapsed. In [[Isabela (province)|Isabela]], \"all work animals\" in [[San Mateo, Isabela|San Mateo]] drowned when the town river overflowed.<ref>{{cite news|author=Inquirer Northern Luzon|newspaper=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]|date=May 9, 2009|accessdate=May 9, 2009|title='Emong' leaves 26 fatalities in north Luzon|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/inquirerheadlines/nation/view/20090509-203990/Emong-leaves-26-fatalities-in-north-Luzon|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090515190839/http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/inquirerheadlines/nation/view/20090509-203990/Emong-leaves-26-fatalities-in-north-Luzon|archive-date=May 15, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe National Disaster Coordinating Council (NDCC) damage report update on 6:00&nbsp;pm May 19 put dead at 60, injured at 53 and missing at 13 and damage worth 1,280,897,383 pesos of which 750,403,562 were in agriculture and 530,493,821 in infrastructure. It further affected 385,833 persons living in 615 barangays of 59 municipalities and 7 cities of 12 provinces of Region I (La Union and Pangasinan), Region II (Nueva Vizcaya, Isabela, Quirino and Cagayan), Region III (Zambales and Pampanga) and Cordillera Administrative Region (Ifugao, Kalinga, Mountain Province and Benguet) as well as damaged 56,160 houses of which 23,444 are totally destroyed and 32,716 partially damaged,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://210.185.184.53/ndccWeb/images/ndccWeb/ndcc_update/emong/ndcc%20update%20situation%20report%20re%20effects%20of%20ts%20emong%2019may2009%206pm.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=October 11, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110530010804/http://210.185.184.53/ndccWeb/images/ndccWeb/ndcc_update/emong/ndcc%20update%20situation%20report%20re%20effects%20of%20ts%20emong%2019may2009%206pm.pdf |archive-date=May 30, 2011 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> and induced 11 landslides in Zambales and Ifugao.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/inquirerheadlines/nation/view/20090508-203768/Emong-lashes-Pangasinan-fells-power-lines|title='Emong' lashes Pangasinan; fells power lines|date=May 8, 2009|newspaper=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]|accessdate=May 8, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090510141742/http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/inquirerheadlines/nation/view/20090508-203768/Emong-lashes-Pangasinan-fells-power-lines|archivedate=May 10, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===June\u2013July===\n[[File:Nangka 2009 at landfall.jpg|thumb|right|Tropical Storm Nangka approaching the Philippines on June 23]]\nIn Eastern Samar, Tropical Storm Nangka left more than 800 people stranded after ferry service was canceled.<ref>{{cite web|author=Staff Writer|publisher=GMA News|date=June 23, 2009|accessdate=June 23, 2009|title=Signal No.1 up over Metro Manila as Feria slams into Borongan, E. Samar|url=http://www.gmanews.tv/story/165639/Signal-No1-up-over-Metro-Manila-as-Feria-slams-into-Borongan-E-Samar}}</ref> High winds downed a large tree, destroying the roof of one home and damaging three cars.<ref>{{cite web|author=Jeannette Andrade|work=Inquirer|date=June 23, 2009|accessdate=June 23, 2009|title=Fallen tree damages 3 cars at DoJ|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/breakingnews/metro/view/20090623-212049/Fallen-tree-damages-3-cars-at-DoJ|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090625025235/http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/breakingnews/metro/view/20090623-212049/Fallen-tree-damages-3-cars-at-DoJ|archivedate=June 25, 2009}}</ref> Unusually strong severe thunderstorms developed over parts of the Philippines along the [[Rainband|outer bands]] of Nangka. In San Pascual, Bauan and Batangas City, large hail fell during a strong storm. Residents reported that they have never seen hail before. In Barangay, 4 in Bauan town, a rare tornado struck, downing several trees, damaging homes and signs. Heavy rains produced by the storm also flooded numerous regions, some reporting waist-deep water.<ref>{{cite web|author=Sarita Kare|publisher=ABS-CBN Southern Tagalog|date=June 23, 2009|accessdate=June 23, 2009|title=Hailstorm, tornado hit Batangas towns |url=http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/nation/regions/06/23/09/hailstorm-tornado-hit-batangas-towns}}</ref> Later reports confirmed the tornado destroyed 23 homes. In Cebu, one person was killed and seven were left missing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gmanews.tv/story/165689/NDCC-1-dead-7-missing-as-Feria-pounds-Cebu|date=June 24, 2009|accessdate=June 24, 2009|title=NDCC: 1 dead, 7 missing as 'Feria' pounds Cebu}}</ref> At least 500 people were also left homeless due to the storm.<ref>{{cite web|author=Alice Nicart |work=Daily News Reader |date=June 24, 2009 |accessdate=June 24, 2009 |title=\"Feria\" leaves 500 homeless; Samar PDCC activated |url=http://www.pia.gov.ph/default.asp?m=12&r=&y=&mo=&fi=p090624.htm&no=24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=http://archives.pia.gov.ph/?m=12&sec=reader&rp=3&fi=p090624.htm&no=24&date= |archivedate=June 24, 2009 }}</ref> In Cavite, 7000 were stranded on the port due to Nangka's winds and heavy rains. about {{convert|4|ft|m}} is the water wave in Cavite.<ref>[http://www.gmanews.tv/video/43871/Cavite_port_stranded Big waves destroy houses \u2013 Video  \u2013 The go-to site for Filipinos everywhere ]. GMA News Retrieved on October 20, 2011.</ref> In [[Albay]], more than 300 ship passengers were also stranded at the Albay port, Tabaco, Albay.<ref>[http://www.gmanews.tv/video/43873/300-ship-passengers-stranded-due-to-%27Feria%27 300 ship passengers stranded due to 'Feria' \u2013 Video  \u2013 The go-to site for Filipinos everywhere ] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20120801022308/http://www.gmanews.tv/video/43873/300-ship-passengers-stranded-due-to-'Feria' |date=August 1, 2012 }}. GMA News Retrieved on October 20, 2011.</ref> In [[Navotas]] and [[Malabon]], the Navotas \u2013 Malabon river produced a {{convert|3|ft|m|adj=on}} high tide in the area.<ref>[http://www.gmanews.tv/video/43872/Navotas-Malabon-in-deep-flood Parts of Metro Manila in deep flood \u2013 Video  \u2013 The go-to site for Filipinos everywhere ]. GMA News Retrieved on October 20, 2011.</ref>\n\nAs of June 24, Nangka (Feria) has caused 6 deaths and left 11 people missing. Property damage from the storm is estimated at PHP 2.8&nbsp;million (US$54,000).<ref>{{cite web|author=Staff Writer|publisher=GMA News TV|date=June 24, 2009|accessdate=June 24, 2009|title=Pagasa: 75 km/h winds won't be felt in Metro Manila; 6 dead, 11 missing|url=http://www.gmanews.tv/story/165713/Feria-roars-across-central-RP-6-dead-11-missing}}</ref>\n\nIn response to Tropical Storm Soudelor, the [[Philippine Atmospheric, Geophysical and Astronomical Services Administration]] issued public storm signal one for nine regions of the northern Philippines.<ref>{{cite web|author=Aie Balagtas|publisher=GMA News TV|date=July 9, 2009|accessdate=July 15, 2009|title=Pagasa hoists signal no. 1 in nine areas|url=http://www.gmanews.tv/story/167039/Pagasa-hoists-signal-no-1-in-nine-areas}}</ref> As a tropical depression, Soudelor brushed northern [[Luzon]] in the Philippines, producing upwards of {{convert|330|mm|in|abbr=on}} of rainfall which resulted in flash flooding and landslides.<ref>{{cite web|author=Dave Samuhel|work=Star Tribune|date=July 12, 2009|accessdate=July 15, 2009|title=Soudelor Brings Heavy Rain To China, Vietnam Sunday|url=http://www.startribune.com/weather/50576522.html?elr=KArks:DCiUBDEaLDyUiacyKUnciaec8O7EyU}}</ref> In [[Ilocos Norte]], major roadways were completely blocked by high waters.<ref name=\"NDCCx\"/> The storm affected 19,845 people throughout the Philippines and one person was killed after being swept away by a fast current.<ref name=\"NDCC2\">{{cite web|author=Glenn J. Rabonza|publisher=National Disaster Coordinating Council|date=July 11, 2009|accessdate=July 15, 2009|title=Situation Report No. 2: Effects of Tropical Depression \"Gorio\"|url=http://210.185.184.53/ndccWeb/images/ndccWeb/ndcc_update/TC_GORIO/sitrep%20no.%202%20re%20effects%20of%20td%20gorio%20as%20of%2011%20july%202009%2C%207pm.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110530011512/http://210.185.184.53/ndccWeb/images/ndccWeb/ndcc_update/TC_GORIO/sitrep%20no.%202%20re%20effects%20of%20td%20gorio%20as%20of%2011%20july%202009,%207pm.pdf|archive-date=May 30, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> At least ten villages were flooded during the storm.<ref>{{cite web|author=Staff Writer|publisher=ABS-CBN News|date=July 10, 2009|accessdate=July 15, 2009|title=Classes suspended in flood-hit Laoag City|url=http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/nation/regions/luzon/07/10/09/classes-suspended-flood-hit-laoag-city|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090717124742/http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/nation/regions/luzon/07/10/09/classes-suspended-flood-hit-laoag-city|archivedate=July 17, 2009}}</ref> Three homes were destroyed and two more were damaged by Soudelor.<ref name=\"NDCCx\"/><ref name=\"NDCC2\"/> A total of 42 [[barangays]] were flooded by the storm, killing 21 cows and isolating low-lying areas.<ref name=\"GorioLeave\">{{cite web|author=Evelyn Macairan, Artemio Dumlao|work=Philippine Star|date=July 12, 2009|accessdate=July 20, 2009|title=New low-pressure area spotted as 'Gorio' leaves RP|url=http://www.philstar.com/Article.aspx?articleId%3D486013%26publicationSubCategoryId%3D63|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5iPTfF7Ub?url=http://www.philstar.com/Article.aspx?articleId=486013&publicationSubCategoryId=63|url-status=dead|archive-date=July 20, 2009}}</ref> On July&nbsp;10, a battalion from the army engineers were deployed to the affected region to repair infrastructure.<ref name=\"NDCCx\">{{cite web|author=Glenn J. Rabonza|publisher=National Disaster Coordinating Council|date=July 10, 2009|accessdate=July 15, 2009|title=Situation Report No. 1: Effects of Tropical Depression \"Gorio\"|url=http://210.185.184.53/ndccWeb/images/ndccWeb/ndcc_update/TC_GORIO/sitrep%20no.%201%20re%20effects%20of%20td%20gorio%20as%20of%2010%20july%202009%2C%206_00pm.pdf|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110530011428/http://210.185.184.53/ndccWeb/images/ndccWeb/ndcc_update/TC_GORIO/sitrep%20no.%201%20re%20effects%20of%20td%20gorio%20as%20of%2010%20july%202009%2C%206_00pm.pdf|archivedate=May 30, 2011}}</ref> Following the storm, the hardest hit town [[Bacarra, Ilocos Norte]], was put under a state of calamity and regional aid was deployed to the area.<ref>{{cite web|author=Staff Writer|publisher=Balita|date=July 11, 2009|accessdate=July 20, 2009|title=Ilocos Norte town placed under state of calamity due to tropical depression \"Gorio\"|url=http://balita.ph/2009/07/11/ilocos-norte-town-placed-under-state-of-calamity-due-to-tropical-depression-gorio/}}</ref>\n\nIn the Philippines Goni (Jolina) death toll is 8 with 5 more missing. Goni (Jolina)  affected 38,589 families or 160,038 people in 119 villages in 25 towns and five cities in [[Ilocos Sur]], [[Batangas]], [[Cagayan]], [[Nueva Ecija]], [[Rizal]], [[Mindoro Occidental]], [[Palawan]], [[Iloilo]], [[Negros Occidental]], [[Lanao del Sur]], and [[Sultan Kudarat]] town in [[Maguindanao]].<ref>[http://ph.news.yahoo.com/gma/20090804/tph-jolina-death-toll-rises-to-8-5-still-ce44f36.html ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090807193523/http://ph.news.yahoo.com/gma/20090804/tph-jolina-death-toll-rises-to-8-5-still-ce44f36.html |date=August 7, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n===August===\n[[File:Typhoon Morakot Aug 7 2009.jpg|thumb|right|Typhoon Morakot north of the Philippines on August 7]]\nTyphoon Morakot, also known as Kiko, produced severe flooding in parts of the Philippines that left 26 people dead. In the [[Philippines]], ten villages (Paudpod, San Juan, Batonloc, Carael, Tampo, Paco, San Miguel, Bining, Bangan, and Capayawan) have been submerged in {{convert|4|to|5|ft|m|adj=mid|-deep}} floods after the Pinatubo Dike overflowed.<ref>[http://www.gmanews.tv/story/169216/Kiko-intensifies-further-4-areas-under-signal-1 'Kiko' intensifies further, 4 areas under signal 1]. GMA News Retrieved on October 20, 2011.</ref> Joint military and police rescue teams rescued 3 Koreans and 9 Canadian nationals. About 30,000 families were affected by Morakot; eleven people are confirmed dead.<ref>{{Citation\n |title       = 'Kiko' death toll rises to 10\n |newspaper   = ABS-CBN News\n |date        = August 7, 2009\n |url         = http://ph.news.yahoo.com/abs/20090807/tph-kiko-death-toll-rises-to9-8061bf7.html\n |accessdate  = August 7, 2009\n |url-status=dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090811021618/http://ph.news.yahoo.com/abs/20090807/tph-kiko-death-toll-rises-to9-8061bf7.html\n |archivedate = August 11, 2009\n |df          = mdy-all\n}}\n</ref><ref>{{Citation\n  | title = 'Kiko' death toll rises to 10; 30K folks affected in Luzon\n  | newspaper=GMANews.TV\n  | date = August 7, 2009\n  | url = http://www.gmanews.tv/story/169221/Kiko-leaves-2-trekkers-dead-15K-folks-affected-in-Luzon\n|accessdate=August 7, 2009}}\n</ref>  Three French tourists and two Filipino guides were killed in a flashflood caused by a landslide.  Thousands are trapped on rooftops or in trees awaiting helicopter rescue attempts and thousands have lost their homes.  At least two have died from flooding.  Landslides have claimed the lives of two children and five miners are still missing after a landslide destroyed their huts.  Schools have suspended their classes in the hardest hit area, and highways have been closed due to landslides.<ref name=\"landslides-floods\">{{Citation\n |title      = Landslide, floods kill 12 in RP\n |newspaper  = Sun Star\n |date       = August 8, 2009\n |url        = http://www.sunstar.com.ph/network/landslide-floods-kill-12-rp\n |archive-url = https://archive.today/20090809165712/http://www.sunstar.com.ph/network/landslide-floods-kill-12-rp\n |url-status   = dead\n |archive-date = August 9, 2009\n |accessdate = August 8, 2009\n}}\n</ref>\n\nIn western Luzon including Manila, a 48-hour rainfall were recorded upon the formation of Tropical Storm Mujigae as a depression. The depression enhanced the southwest monsoon that brought torrential rains in the area. In Laguna, two children were killed due to landslides caused by torrential rains brought by ''Maring''. Late on September 8, both the JMA and the PAGASA declared the system was a minor tropical depression. Also, on September 9, all classes in Manila was suspended from Pre \u2013 school, Elementary school, and High school due to incessant raining and flooding. The National Disaster Coordinating Council reported that at least three villages in Malabon City were submerged in {{convert|18|in|mm|adj=mid|-deep}} floodwaters. At least four streets in the area were impassable to light vehicles. Also on that day, six provinces was raised in public storm signal no. 1.<ref>[http://ph.news.yahoo.com/star/20090909/tph-signal-no-hoisted-over-areas due-mar-541dfb4.html]{{dead link|date=October 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Valenzuela, Philippines|Valenzuela City]], 15 low-lying barangays located in the city's first district are underwater. In Bulacan, five towns and two cities of the province are flooded, with water as high as four feet. In Bataan, the town of Dinalupihan was placed under state of calamity after 22 barangays were affected by flash floods. In Pampanga, the NDCC placed the towns of Sta.Ana, San Luis, Minalin, Mexico, Macabebe, Masantol, Apalit, Guagua, Sasmuan, Lubao, and Bacolor in state of calamity due of rivers in Tarlac are swelling.\n\nMore than 300, 000 residents of four northern provinces were affected by floods, including about 3,300 people who fled to evacuation centers and more than 41,000 who moved in with their relatives and friends. Overall damages were estimated of 25 million [[PHP|Philippine Peso]] in agricultural land.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ph.news.yahoo.com/abs/20090909/tph-deped-suspends-elementary-highschool-898cf49.html|title=DepEd suspends elementary, highschool classes in metro |accessdate=October 11, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090914154241/http://ph.news.yahoo.com/abs/20090909/tph-deped-suspends-elementary-highschool-898cf49.html |archivedate=September 14, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n===September\u2013October===\nThe most significant loss of life and damage took place during late September and early October from the combined effects of Typhoons Ketsana and Parma. Together, the two storms killed over 600 people and left more than $300&nbsp;million in damages.\n\n====Tropical Storm Ketsana====\n[[File:Tropical Storm Ketsana September 26, 2009.jpg|thumb|right|Tropical Storm Ketsana over the Philippines on September 26]]\nDuring Typhoon Ketsana, on the afternoon of September 26, Teodoro declared an overall [[state of calamity]] in Metro Manila and other 25 provinces hit by the typhoon, allowing officials to utilize emergency funds for relief and rescue.<ref>[http://www.nguoi-viet.com/absolutenm/anmviewer.asp?a=101853&z=5 L\u1ee5t \u1edf Phi Lu\u1eadt T\u00e2n: 50 ng\u01b0\u1eddi ch\u1ebft]{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} {{in lang|vi}}</ref> Army troops, police and civilian volunteers were deployed to rescue victims.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gmanews.tv/story/173229/metro-manila-25-provinces-placed-under-state-of-calamity|title=Metro Manila, 25 provinces placed under state of calamity|date=September 26, 2009|publisher=GMA News|accessdate=September 29, 2009}}</ref> The [[Philippine National Red Cross]] and [[Philippine Coast Guard]] dispatched teams to rescue stranded and trapped people.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/breakingnews/metro/view/20090927-227182/Red-Cross-rubber-boats-rescue-people-on-roofs|title=Red Cross rubber boats rescue people on roofs|last=Andrade|first=Jeannette|date=September 27, 2009|newspaper=Philippine Daily Inquirer|accessdate=September 29, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090930091108/http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/breakingnews/metro/view/20090927-227182/Red-Cross-rubber-boats-rescue-people-on-roofs|archive-date=September 30, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> At that time, flood average was from two-feet to waist high, and in some areas are more than six feet.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gmanews.tv/story/173220/floods-rise-to-6-feet-in-rizal-residents-ask-for-rescue|title=Floods rise to 6 feet in Rizal; residents ask for rescue|date=September 26, 2009|publisher=GMA News|accessdate=September 29, 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe resulting landslides and severe flooding left at least 246 people dead and 38 others missing.<ref name=\"Why\">Ishaan Tharoor, \"Philippine Floods: Why Wasn't Manila Prepared?\" Time magazine, September 29, 2009, found at [https://news.yahoo.com/s/time/20090929/wl_time/08599192664600 Yahoo News].  Accessed September 29, 2009.</ref><ref name=\"NDCC update\">{{cite web|url=http://210.185.184.53/ndccWeb/images/ndccWeb/ndcc_advisory/TC_ONDOY/ondoy15.pdf|title=Situation Report: Ondoy|accessdate=September 29, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110530012257/http://210.185.184.53/ndccWeb/images/ndccWeb/ndcc_advisory/TC_ONDOY/ondoy15.pdf|archivedate=May 30, 2011}}</ref> Public and private roads were clogged by vehicles stuck in floodwater.<ref name=\"Why\" /> Thousands of motorists and more than 500 passengers were stranded at the [[North Luzon Expressway]] (NLEx). Distress calls and e-mails from thousands of Metro Manila and their worried relatives flooded TV and radio stations overnight as most of the power, communication and water lines were lost.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bworldonline.com/BW092909/content.php?src=3&id=072|title=Metro Manila, surrounding areas' power, water supply still below normal|last=Santos|first=Jose Bimbo|date=September 29, 2009|accessdate=September 29, 2009}}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Ketsana also caused the shutting down of flights and operations at the [[Ninoy Aquino International Airport]] for almost a day.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rmn.ph/national/libulibong-pasahero-nastranded-sa-naia-dahil-sa-pananalasa-bagyong-ondoy|title=Libu-libong pasahero, na-stranded sa NAIA dahil sa pananalasa Bagyong Ondoy|date=September 27, 2009|language=Tagalog|accessdate=September 29, 2009}} {{Dead link|date=November 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\nThe economic region of [[Metro Manila]] and many adjoining provinces incurred damages to both [[infrastructure]] and agriculture. Total damage of Ketsana as of September 28, 2009 is estimated at $100&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"Why\" /><ref name=\"yahoo\">{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2009/sep/28/death-toll-philippine-storm-reaches-100/ |title=140 die in Philippine storm, toll expected to rise|last=Cerojano|first=Teresa|author2=Associated Press |date=September 28, 2009|work=The Washington Times|accessdate=October 1, 2009|author2-link=Associated Press}}</ref><ref name=\"damaged\">Katherine Evangelista, \"SAYS NDCC: P109-M worth of infrastructure, crops damaged: Death toll up to 100, September 28, 2009, found at [http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/breakingnews/nation/view/20090928-227311/P109-M-worth-of-infrastructure-crops-damaged INQUIRER.net website] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090929165428/http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/breakingnews/nation/view/20090928-227311/P109-M-worth-of-infrastructure-crops-damaged |date=September 29, 2009 }}.  Accessed September 28, 2009.</ref> [[Internet caf\u00e9]]s, entertainment plazas, banks, food stores, building agencies and stores were soaked into flood and mud.<ref name=\"Why\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gmanews.tv/story/173294/both-rich-and-poor-suffered-from-ondoys-wrath|title=Both rich and poor suffered from Ondoy's wrath|last=Arquiza|first=Yasmin|date=September 28, 2009|publisher=GMA News|accessdate=September 29, 2009}}</ref>\n\nCompared to other storm-hit areas in the [[Philippines]], [[Marikina City]], was the most devastated region where almost all of the city's area was submerged in water not more than ten feet and tons of knee-deep mud. During the typhoon, [[Marikina River]] broke off from its banks and transformed streets into rivers of flood.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/8278818.stm|title=Devastation in Manila flood zone |last=Leithead|first=Alastair|date=September 28, 2009|work=BBC News |accessdate=September 29, 2009}}</ref> The breakage of the river from its dike causes heavy flooding on other Metro Manila streets. Marikina residential areas, particularly Provident Village, was highly spawned by flood were at least eight people were found dead.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gmanews.tv/story/173269/8-dead-in-provident-village-marikina-city|title=8 dead in Provident Village, Marikina City|last=de los Santos|first=Melissa|date=September 28, 2009|publisher=GMA News|accessdate=September 29, 2009}}</ref> Marikina itself recorded 78 deaths, the highest among Metro Manila cities.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/nation/09/28/09/78-dead-devastated-marikina|title=78 dead in devastated Marikina|last=Aragones|first=Sol|date=September 28, 2009|publisher=ABS-CBN News|accessdate=September 29, 2009}}</ref>\n\nAt the height of the flooding, around 100,000 liters bunker oil from the paper manufacturing firm Noah's Paper Mill in [[Marikina City]] spilled when pressurized by the surge. Most of the oil battered the city's [[barangay]]s and small comparable amount combined with the [[Marikina River]] and basement of [[SM City Marikina]]. The spill will later complicate rescue efforts in the city.<ref>{{cite news|title=Oil spill complicates Marikina rescue efforts|url=http://www.mb.com.ph/articles/222424/oil-spill-complicates-marikina-rescue-efforts|first=Aaron|last=Recuenco|date=September 28, 2009|newspaper=Philippine Daily Inquirer|accessdate=September 28, 2009}}</ref> On September 29, [[National Power Corporation|National Power Corporation Flood Forecasting and Warning System]] released 500 cubic meters of stored water from the [[Angat Dam]] in [[Bulacan]] over a two-day period. The dam accumulated 100 cubic meters of water when Ketsana hit the province.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bulacan residents warned of Angat Dam water release|url=http://www.gmanews.tv/story/173363/bulacan-residents-warned-of-angat-dam-water-release|author=Kim Tan|accessdate=September 29, 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Mindanao]], several towns in [[Cotabato City]] and nearby [[Sultan Kudarat]] municipalities were submerged. The closing of national highway in Bulalo, Cotabato City led to the isolation of connecting towns for several days.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/breakingnews/regions/view/20090928-227314/Ondoy-worsens-floods-in-Mindanao-town-villages|title='Ondoy' worsens floods in Mindanao town, villages|last=Se\u00f1ase|first=Charlie|date=September 28, 2009|publisher=Inquirer Mindanao|accessdate=September 29, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090929102750/http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/breakingnews/regions/view/20090928-227314/Ondoy-worsens-floods-in-Mindanao-town-villages|archive-date=September 29, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn September 28, an 11&nbsp;am advisory of PAG-ASA was issued canceling all public storm signals in the country when Ketsana left [[Philippine Area of Responsibility]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gmanews.tv/story/173263/pagasa-lifts-all-storm-signals-in-rp-more-rains-to-follow-as-ondoy-exits|title=Pagasa lifts all Storm Signals in RP; more rains to follow as 'Ondoy' exits|date=September 28, 2009|publisher=GMA News|accessdate=September 29, 2009}}</ref>\n\n====Typhoon Parma====\n[[File:ParmaMelor AMO TMO 2009279 lrg.jpg|thumb|Severe Tropical Storm Parma as it made landfall in Northern Luzon for the second time after [[Fujiwhara effect|interacting]] with [[Typhoon Melor (2009)|Typhoon Melor]] on October 6]]\nEven though Parma would not make its landfall<ref>[http://www.nguoi-viet.com/absolutenm/anmviewer.asp?a=102457&z=5 H\u01a1n 160 ng\u01b0\u1eddi ch\u1ebft v\u00ec \u0111\u1ea5t chu\u1ed3i \u1edf Phi Lu\u1eadt T\u00e2n]{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} {{in lang|vi}}</ref> in northern Philippines, various transportation was suspended before the super typhoon drew near.<ref>[http://www.nguoi-viet.com/absolutenm/anmviewer.asp?a=102165&z=5 Ketsana v\u1eeba qua, Parma l\u1ea1i t\u1edbi: H\u00e0ng ch\u1ee5c ng\u00e0n d\u00e2n Philippines b\u1ecf ch\u1ea1y tr\u1ed1n tr\u1eadn b\u00e3o m\u1edbi]{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} {{in lang|vi}}</ref> In [[Catanduanes]], where the first signal warning no.3 was raised, the province's power and communications were cut. Fallen trees were already in the main roads. About 30,000 families were evacuated. In addition also to the [[Bicol Region|Bicol]] region, more than 2,000 passengers were stranded in ferry stations.<ref>[http://www.gmanews.tv/story/173671/isabela-aurora-bicol-region-begin-evacuations Isabela, Aurora, Bicol region begin evacuations]. GMA News. October 2, 2009.</ref> 39 provinces including Metro Manila were put to signal warnings, with each place experienced massive rainfall with strong winds. Parma made its landfall at Northeastern Cagayan at 3:00&nbsp;pm PST/07:00 (UTC). In [[Cagayan]], at least 6,036 people in 39 barangays (villages) were affected, while P20.33&nbsp;million worth of agricultural produce were destroyed. Also, in the Chico River was swelled due to the typhoon, making the Maguilling Overflow Bridge along the Cagayan-Apayao Road impassable. The Maharlika Highway in Ilagan, Isabela to Cagayan became hardly passable due to the trees and electric posts that fell when Pepeng battered the area. Total power interruption also crippled the provinces of Kalinga, Apayao, and the northern towns of Isabela. In Kalinga, landslides were reported on roads linking the provincial capital, Tabuk, to upland towns. In Zambales, at least 2,100 families were evacuated as Pepeng brought heavy rains causing the Bucao River to swell.<ref>[http://www.nguoi-viet.com/absolutenm/anmviewer.asp?a=102549&z=5 B\u00e3o l\u0169 l\u00e0m ch\u1ebft 600 ng\u01b0\u1eddi Philippines: L\u00ednh M\u1ef9 gi\u00fap c\u1ee9u tr\u1ee3] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091014002352/http://www.nguoi-viet.com/absolutenm/anmviewer.asp?a=102549&z=5 |date=October 14, 2009 }} {{in lang|vi}}</ref> The Carael section of the Zambales highway became impassable due to rising floodwaters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gmanews.tv/story/173750/pepeng-plunges-ne-luzon-into-darkness-4-people-killed |title='Pepeng' downs power and cell services in NE Luzon |publisher=GMANews.TV |date=October 3, 2009 |accessdate=October 9, 2009}}</ref> Due to heavy downpour, the [[San Roque Dam (Philippines)|San Roque Dam]] in Eastern [[Pangasinan]] and [[Pantabangan Dam]] in [[Nueva Ecija]] was forced to release huge amount of water. It caused flooding in Eastern and Central Pangasinan as well as Nueva Ecija. In [[Metro Manila]] the area is still experienced torrential rains and strong winds. Floodwaters continue to rise in some areas in Metro Manila and [[Calabarzon]]. In [[Pateros, Metro Manila|Pateros]], [[Muntinlupa]], and [[Taguig]], in [[Taytay, Rizal|Taytay]] town in Rizal province, and in the towns of [[Bi\u00f1an]] and [[San Pedro, Laguna|San Pedro]] in [[Laguna Province|Laguna]] province, the flood is not subsiding. The [[Laguna de Bay]] is breaking a 90-year record in meters of water, which threatens to submerge more areas in Metro Manila.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gmanews.tv/story/173742/floodwaters-continue-to-rise-in-metro-manila-calabarzon-areas |title=Floodwaters continue to rise in Metro Manila, Calabarzon areas |publisher=GMANews.TV |date=October 3, 2009 |accessdate=October 9, 2009}}</ref> In [[Benguet]], a landslide killed at least 200 as Tropical Depression Parma continues to bring rain across northern [[Luzon]].<ref>[http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/nation/10/09/09/100-reported-killed-cordillera-landslides (''ABS-CBN News'')]</ref><ref>[http://nguoi-viet.com/absolutenm/anmviewer.asp?a=103527&z=5 M\u1ed9t th\u00e1ng b\u1ed1n c\u01a1n b\u00e3o ho\u00e0nh h\u00e0nh Philippines]{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} {{in lang|vi}}</ref>\n\n===Rest of the year===\n[[File:Mirinae Oct 30 2009 0500Z.jpg|thumb|right|Typhoon Mirinae approaching the Philippines on October 30]]\nThe rest of the year saw six more storms, but only two made landfall and added some more damage already caused by Ketsana and Parma.\n\nWhile Parma (Pepeng) was still drifting over northern Luzon, [[Typhoon Melor (2009)|Melor]] entered PAGASA's area of responsibility, and therefore was named Quedan.<ref>[http://www.gmanews.tv/story/173861/rp-faces-2-cyclones-as-quedan-enters-territory RP faces 2 cyclones as \u2018Quedan\u2019 enters territory]. GMA News Retrieved on October 20, 2011.</ref> While it did not make landfall on any part of the country, its interaction with Typhoon Parma would cause Melor to weaken and shift course to Japan while Parma crossed Northern Luzon three times, therefore bringing rain, wind and destruction over the area.<ref>[http://www.gmanews.tv/story/173911/39quedan39-weakens-may-leave-rp-tuesday-night-pagasa 'Quedan' weakens, may leave RP Tuesday night \u2013 Pagasa]. GMA News Retrieved on October 20, 2011.</ref>\n\n[[Typhoon Lupit (2009)|Lupit (Ramil)]] was the next typhoon to directly hit any part of the Philippines,<ref>[http://www.gmanews.tv/story/174842/storm-39ramil39-enters-rp-area-of-responsibility-pagasa Storm 'Ramil' enters RP area of responsibility \u2013 Pagasa]. GMA News Retrieved on October 20, 2011.</ref> having threatened the areas already ravaged by Typhoon Parma. While initially forecasted by PAGASA to cross Cagayan or Batanes by,<ref name=\"gmanews.tv\">[http://www.gmanews.tv/story/175354/pagasa-ramil-to-make-landfall-late-friday-or-early-saturday Pagasa: Ramil to make landfall late Friday or early Saturday]. GMA News Retrieved on October 20, 2011.</ref> Ramil eventually veered northeast in spite of strengthening, sparing the areas still recovering from Pepeng's wrath. However, it brought little to moderate rain from Cagayan to as far as Southern Luzon. Despite this incident, local governments in Northern Luzon prepared for the worst, even putting medical personnel on \"Code Blue\" (on-duty 24/7) and having army contingents sent out by the national government<ref name=\"gmanews.tv\"/><ref>[http://www.gmanews.tv/story/174965/as-39ramil39-heads-for-rp-govt-vows-to-be-ready-this-time As 'Ramil' heads for RP, govt vows to be ready this time]. GMA News Retrieved on October 20, 2011.</ref> It also forced planes and buses, especially those going north, to suspend trips.<ref>[http://www.gmanews.tv/story/175222/ramil-forces-cancellation-of-domestic-flights-bus-trips Ramil forces cancellation of domestic flights, bus trips]. GMA News Retrieved on October 20, 2011.</ref> Dams also released water, exactly like when Parma hit the area.<ref>[http://www.gmanews.tv/story/175088/pagasa-39ramil39-to-be-felt-tuesday-night-signal-2-in-5-areas Pagasa: 'Ramil' to be felt Tuesday night; signal 2 in 5 areas]. GMA News Retrieved on October 20, 2011.</ref>\n\n[[Typhoon Mirinae (2009)|Mirinae (Santi)]] was the last significant storm to make landfall on any part of the country. It took the similar direction that Ondoy went through as it wreaked havoc over Philippines, and therefore again hitting the capital Manila and nearby provinces.<ref>[http://www.gmanews.tv/story/175856/santi-may-make-landfall-friday-night-may-hit-mmanila Santi may make landfall Friday night, may hit MManila]. GMA News Retrieved on October 20, 2011.</ref> Hitting just before the Philippine holiday, All Saints' Day, it went through [[Quezon Province]], [[Batangas]] and [[Cavite]].<ref>[http://www.gmanews.tv/story/176002/typhoon-santi-slightly-veers-south-metro-still-threatened Typhoon Santi slightly veers south, Metro still threatened]. GMA News Retrieved on October 20, 2011.</ref> It lashed strong winds, rain,<ref>[http://www.gmanews.tv/story/175916/santi-packs-150kph-winds-may-hit-cluzon-saturday Santi packs 150 km/h winds, may hit CLuzon Saturday]. GMA News Retrieved on October 20, 2011.</ref> and added some more damage to the areas still recovering from Ondoy, especially flooded areas in Rizal Province and Laguna.<ref>[http://www.gmanews.tv/story/175976/with-signal-no-3-typhoon-santi-wrecks-holiday-plans With signal no. 3, Typhoon Santi wrecks holiday plans]. GMA News Retrieved on October 20, 2011.</ref> But its passage is rather quick; this spared the affected areas from further devastation;<ref>[http://www.gmanews.tv/story/176014/39the-worst-is-over39-santi-now-over-south-china-sea 'The worst is over'; Santi now over South China Sea]. GMA News Retrieved on October 20, 2011.</ref> however, it left at least 13 dead.<ref>[http://www.gmanews.tv/story/176030/39santi39-moves-further-away-from-rp-at-least-13-killed 'Santi' moves further away from RP; at least 13 killed]. GMA News Retrieved on October 20, 2011.</ref> Dams also released water, like what happened when Parma hit Northern Luzon.<ref>[http://www.gmanews.tv/story/175841/typhoon-signal-up-as-39santi39-intensifies-dams-urged-to-release-water Typhoon signal up as 'Santi' intensifies; dams urged to release water]. GMA News Retrieved on October 20, 2011.</ref> Power outages became widespread especially over Manila as Santi was over Southern Tagalog region;<ref>[http://www.gmanews.tv/story/176008/39santi39-causes-floods-brownouts-in-metro-manila-luzon 'Santi' causes floods, brownouts in Metro Manila, Luzon]. GMA News Retrieved on October 20, 2011.</ref> they were subsequently restored\n\nTropical depression Urduja brought torrential rain over Visayas, killing four people and making roads impassable over the affected areas.<ref>[http://www.gmanews.tv/story/178024/4-dead-in-39urduja39-wake-some-roads-impassable 4 dead in 'Urduja' wake, some roads impassable]. GMA News Retrieved on October 20, 2011.</ref>\n\nTropical depression Tino and [[Typhoon Nida (2009)|Typhoon Nida (Vinta)]] were observed over PAGASA's area of responsibility, but did little to no damage.\n<!--\n==Aftermath==\n===National responses===\n===International responses===-->\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Tropical cyclones}}\n*[[Typhoon]]\n*[[Typhoons in the Philippines]]\n*[[2009 Pacific typhoon season]]\n*[[Effects of the 2013 Pacific typhoon season in the Philippines]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{2009 Philippine typhoon season buttons}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Effects Of The 2009 Pacific Typhoon Season In The Philippines}}\n[[Category:2009 Pacific typhoon season]]\n[[Category:2009 disasters in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Typhoons in the Philippines]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n[[File:2009 deadly Philippine typhoons.png|250px|thumb|right|Tracks of all storms affecting the Philippines in 2009]]\nThe '''effects of the [[2009 Pacific typhoon season]] in the [[Philippines]]''' were considered some of the worst in decades. Throughout the year, series of typhoons impacted the country, with the worst damage occurring during September and October from Typhoons Ketsana and Parma.\n\nThe season started by the formation of Tropical Depression Auring during early of the year which affected southern Philippines with moderate damages. Only two storms, Bising and Crising, developed during the weak first third of the season, with later Dante and Emong forming and impacting [[Luzon]] during the first week of May. Tropical Storm Feria impacted most of the country with severe damages during June. A series of weak storms developed continuously during July.\n\nTyphoon Kiko only brushed the norther part of the Philippine's area of Responsibility while enhancing the [[southwest monsoon]], which caused heavy flooding throughout the country. During late-September, combined with the enhancement of the monsoon, Ondoy formed and affected most of the country with an extreme death toll and extensive damages. Typhoons Pepeng and Quedan formed along a week after Ondoy, but both typhoons [[Fujiwhara effect|interacted]] together which made Pepeng affect northern Luzon for a long time. During late-October to early-November, Typhoon Santi made landfall over central Luzon with major damages. Vinta was the last storm to enter or form within the PAR during the season without even affecting the country.\n\n<div class=\"noprint\" style=\"clear:right; border:solid #aaa 1px; margin:0 0 1em 1em; font-size:85%; line-height:1.5; background:#f9f9f9; width:250px; padding:4px; spacing:0; text-align:left; float:right;\">\n{|\n|-\n|rowspan=4| '''Related articles'''\n|'''[[2009 Pacific typhoon season]]'''\n|-\n|[[Timeline of the 2009 Pacific typhoon season]]\n|}\n</div>\n\n==Seasonal statistics==\n[[File:2009 Pacific typhoon season summary.png|thumb|left|Tracks of all tropical cyclones in the western Pacific basin during 2009]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float:center;\"\n|- \"\n! Name\n! PAGASA<br />name\n! Dates of impact\n! Fatalities\n! Damages<br /><small>(Millions US$)</small>\n! Maximum intensity<br />during passage\n|-\n| ---- || ''[[Tropical Depression Auring (2009)|Auring]]'' || <center>January 4\u20137</center> || <center>2</center> || <center>0.498</center> ||style=\"background: #{{Storm colour|depression}};\" | <center>Tropical Depression</center>\n|-\n| ---- || ''[[2009 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Depression Bising|Bising]]'' || <center>February 12\u201313</center> || <center>0</center> || <center>Minimal</center> || style=\"background: #{{Storm colour|depression}};\" | <center>Tropical Depression</center>\n|-\n| ---- || ''[[2009 Pacific typhoon season#Tropical Depression Crising|Crising]]'' || <center>May 1</center> || <center>0</center> || <center>Minimal</center> || style=\"background: #{{Storm colour|depression}};\" | <center>Tropical Depression</center>\n|-\n| [[Typhoon Kujira (2009)|Kujira]] |